      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## **THE MAP OF MI'KMA'KI**\n\nTake a close look at the map on the left. It transports us back to a very different version of Nova Scotia. In 1752, the province we know today was effectively a small British military outpost huddled around the fortifications of Halifax. The vast majority of the territory—the forests, the rivers, the hunting grounds—was **Mi'kma'ki**. This was, and legally remains, the unceded ancestral land of the Mi'kmaq people.\n\nAt that time, the British were not the masters of this land; they were visitors. They were outnumbered and desperate for peace. The conflict with the Mi'kmaq had made it dangerous for settlers to venture beyond the city walls. To end the violence and secure their own survival, the British Crown entered into the **Peace and Friendship Treaty of 1752**.\n\n**A Trade Agreement, Not a Surrender**\n\nIt is crucial to understand that this treaty was **not** a land surrender. The Mi'kmaq did not give up their territory. Instead, it was a \"Peace and Friendship\" agreement—essentially a contract to live side-by-side. Central to this contract was trade. The British knew they couldn't conquer the Mi'kmaq, so they decided to trade with them. The Crown promised to build a **\"Truckhouse\"**—a government-run trading post—at the Shubenacadie River. \n\n**Leo's Argument Today**\n\nFast forward to today. Leo Francis, the owner of the Trading Post, argues that this promise is not just a dusty historical footnote. He says, \"You promised us a place to trade so we wouldn't be cheated. You promised us an economy. You can't just cancel that deal because 270 years have passed.\" The Province argues the Truckhouse system ended in the 1700s, making the clause obsolete. However, Leo insists that the right to trade is the supreme law of the land, protected by the Constitution. He believes the Trading Post he operates today is the modern equivalent of the Truckhouse promised to his ancestors.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/truckhouse-map.jpg",
          "credit": "Map of 1760 Truckhouse Locations"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## **THE WORDS THAT MATTER**\n\nIn constitutional law, specific words have immense power. We must examine Article 4 of the Treaty of 1752 with a magnifying glass. The text states:\n\n> *\"It is agreed that the said Tribe... shall have free liberty to bring for Sale... Skins, Feathers, Fowl, Fish or **ANY OTHER THING** they shall have to sell...\"*\n\n**The Loophole: \"Any Other Thing\"**\n\nLeo's entire legal defense hangs on those three bolded words: **\"Any other thing.\"** \n\nLeo's lawyers are using a legal principle called the **\"Living Tree\" doctrine**. This doctrine is a fundamental rule in Canadian law that says the Constitution is not a dead piece of paper; it is a \"living tree\" that grows and adapts to new situations. For example, the Constitution gives the federal government control over \"Telegraphs.\" A strict reading would mean they don't control the internet. But under the Living Tree doctrine, \"Telegraphs\" evolves to include \"Telephones\" and then \"Internet.\" \n\n**The Evolution of Trade**\n\nLeo applies this logic to the Treaty. In 1752, \"any other thing\" meant beaver pelts, moose hides, and moccasins because that’s what the economy was. Today, the economy includes timber, lobster, and yes—cannabis. Leo argues that if the British promised his ancestors the right to sell \"any thing\" they had, that right must evolve to include modern goods. To rule otherwise is to freeze Indigenous rights in the past, treating the Mi'kmaq as museum exhibits rather than participants in the modern economy.\n\n**The Crown's Counter**\n\nThe Crown argues for a stricter interpretation. They claim that the parties in 1752 could never have imagined the trade of psychoactive drugs like cannabis. They argue that \"any other thing\" implies safe, traditional goods, not controlled substances that require strict government regulation.",
          "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/36/1752_Peace_and_Friendship_Treaty.jpg",
          "credit": "Original 1752 Treaty Parchment"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## **THE WAMPUM BELT**\n\n**EVIDENCE:** Oral History & Wampum\n\nWhile the British recorded their laws on parchment with ink, the Mi'kmaq recorded theirs in **Wampum Belts**. These are intricate patterns of purple and white beads made from quahog shells. They are not just decoration; they are legal documents. The belt shown here depicts a chain of friendship, symbolizing a relationship of **\"Brother to Brother\"** rather than \"Subject to King.\"\n\n**Reading the Wampum**\n\nAn Elder testified in court to explain the meaning of this belt. He said: \"We never surrendered. We agreed to share the land. When you share, you don't tell your partner what they are allowed to do. You respect them. The chain needs polishing—it needs renewal—but the bond is equal.\"\n\n**Intelligence Assessment**\n\nFrom an intelligence perspective, this fundamentally shifts the power dynamic of the courtroom. \n\n* **If the Crown is right:** The Mi'kmaq are subjects of Canada, and Canada makes the rules. The Treaty is just a contract that Canada can regulate.\n* **If the Wampum is right:** The Mi'kmaq are sovereign partners (brothers). If they are partners, the Province of Nova Scotia has no right to dictate their business practices. The Elder argues that the Province is trying to act like a strict parent, punishing a child. But the Treaty proves they are equals.\n\nThis evidence challenges the very foundation of the Crown's authority. It suggests that the \"Rule of Law\" the government speaks of is actually a violation of the original \"Law of the Land\" established by the Wampum.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/wampum-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "Wampum Belt Archive"
        }
      }
