          "body": "## **THE BAND COUNCIL RESOLUTION (BCR)**\n\nThe document taped to the glass door of the Trading Post is not a protest sign. It is a **Band Council Resolution (BCR)**. \n\n**What is a BCR?**\n\nA BCR is a piece of legislation passed by the Chief and Council of a First Nation. Under the *Indian Act*, Band Councils have the power to make bylaws for the \"peace, order, and good government\" of the reserve. \n\n**The Constitutional Crisis**\n\nThis specific BCR explicitly declares that the Province of Nova Scotia has **no jurisdiction** to enforce the *Cannabis Control Act* on Millbrook First Nation lands. It asserts that the First Nation is the sole regulator of cannabis within its territory. This creates a direct conflict between two legal systems:\n\n1.  **The Province:** Holds a Search Warrant authorized by the *Cannabis Control Act*. They claim provincial laws of \"general application\" apply to everyone in the province, including on reserves.\n2.  **The Band:** Holds a Resolution authorized by Indigenous Sovereignty and Section 35 of the Constitution. They claim they have the inherent right to manage their own economy.\n\n**The Core Question**\n\nWhich piece of paper is more powerful? If you rule that the Provincial Warrant is supreme, you are saying that Indigenous governments are subordinate to the province. If you rule that the BCR is supreme, you might be creating a \"legal vacuum\" where provincial safety laws don't apply. The Supreme Court has struggled with this balance for decades.",
