          "body": "## **LEO SPEAKS**\n\nLeo Francis takes the stand. He is not wearing a suit; he wears a ribbon shirt, a symbol of Indigenous pride. He holds an Eagle Feather, signifying his oath to speak the absolute truth—a vow far more binding to him than swearing on a Bible. He addresses the court with a calm, defiant logic that cuts through the legal jargon.\n\n**The Musket Argument**\n\n\"The Crown says cannabis is dangerous,\" Leo begins. \"They say they have to ban it to protect the public. But look at our history. In 1760, what did the British trade with us? **Muskets. Gunpowder. Lead shot. Rum.**\"\n\nHe pauses to let that sink in. \n\n**The Logic of Hypocrisy**\n\nLeo points out a historical hypocrisy. In the 18th century, the British were happy to trade deadly weapons and alcohol when it suited their needs. Muskets were the most dangerous technology of the day—designed to kill. Yet, the Treaty protected the trade of those items. \n\nLeo asks the Judge: \"If the Treaty protected the trade of muskets and gunpowder, how can the Crown now claim that cannabis—a plant—is 'too dangerous' to be protected?\" He argues that 'safety' is just a convenient excuse the government uses when they want to control the market. He asserts that his people have managed dangerous goods for centuries without the Province's help.",
