          "credit": "Leo Francis"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## **SECTION 35: THE PROTECTOR**\n\nLeo's defense team rests their case heavily on **Section 35 of the Constitution Act, 1982**. This is a pivotal piece of legislation. Before 1982, the government could easily cancel Indigenous rights. But Section 35 changed everything. It states: \n\n> *\"The existing aboriginal and treaty rights of the aboriginal peoples of Canada are hereby recognized and affirmed.\"*\n\n**The 'Full Box' Theory**\n\nLeo's lawyers are arguing for what is known as the **'Full Box' theory** of rights. Imagine Section 35 is a box. \n\n* **The Crown's View (Empty Box):** The box is empty. Rights only get put into the box when a court proves they exist or the government grants them. Until then, Leo has no rights.\n* **The Defense View (Full Box):** The box is already packed full. It contains inherent rights—like the right to self-government, economic independence, and stewardship of the land—that existed for thousands of years before Canada was even a country.\n\nLeo contends that he doesn't need a judge's permission (or a provincial license) to exercise a right his people have held since before the Pyramids were built. He argues that Section 35 protects his right to earn a living, and the Province is illegally trying to empty his box.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/indian-act-book.jpg",
          "credit": "Constitution Act, 1982"
