          "body": "## **UNDRIP AND ECONOMIC RIGHTS**\n\n**CONTEXT:** International Law (UNDRIP)\n\nThe defense is expanding the battlefield beyond Canadian law. They are citing the **United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP)**, specifically **Article 20**.\n\n**What is Article 20?**\n\nIt states that Indigenous peoples have the right to \"maintain and develop their political, economic and social systems or institutions.\" It essentially says: You have a human right to run your own economy.\n\n**The Strategy: Shaming the Crown**\n\nBy invoking UNDRIP, the defense is internationalizing the case. They are arguing that the **\"Truckhouse Clause\"** should be interpreted through the lens of Article 20. This means the Treaty isn't just about trading furs; it's about the right to a **Moderate Livelihood** in the modern world. \n\nIf the Mi'kmaq cannot participate in the modern economy (cannabis, fisheries, timber) on their own terms, they are being denied their basic human right to economic survival. This argument is designed to shame Canada on the global stage. Canada recently passed a law (the *UNDA*) promising to implement UNDRIP. If the court rules against Leo, the defense will argue that Canada is breaking its promises to the United Nations.",
