          "body": "## **THE GOVERNMENT'S CASE**\n\nThe Justice Minister holds a press conference at the Provincial Legislature. He is flanked by serious-looking police chiefs and health officials, presenting a united front of \"Law and Order.\"\n\n**The Message: \"Reconciliation is not Lawlessness\"**\n\nThe Minister speaks carefully. \"We respect the Treaties,\" he says. \"We are committed to reconciliation. But reconciliation does not mean lawlessness. The Supreme Court has repeatedly said that Treaty Rights are not unlimited. We cannot have a patchwork of laws where some stores follow safety rules and others do not.\"\n\n**The Trap: The Googoo Precedent**\n\nThe Government is relying heavily on a recent court ruling: **R. v. Googoo (2024)**. In that case, a judge hinted that cannabis might not be protected because it lacks \"historical continuity.\" \n\n**The Frozen Rights Argument**\n\nThe Crown's logic is simple: The Mi'kmaq didn't smoke or trade cannabis in 1752. Therefore, they have no traditional right to sell it today. They are trying to **\"Freeze\"** Indigenous rights in the 18th century. They argue that Treaty rights only apply to things the Mi'kmaq actually did back then—like fishing or hunting. Since cannabis is a \"new\" drug, the Crown claims it falls 100% under provincial control.",
