          "body": "## **THE GOOGOO PRECEDENT**\n\n**THE CASE:** *R. v. Googoo (2024)*\n\nThis is the biggest hurdle for Leo's defense. In a similar case just last year, the judge ruled against the dispensary owners. \n\n**Why Googoo Lost**\n\nThe court found that while the Mi'kmaq have a right to trade, they do not have a right to trade *illegal* goods. Since cannabis is a \"controlled substance\" under federal law, the judge ruled it falls outside the Treaty's protection unless the First Nation has a federally approved regulatory system in place.\n\n**Distinguishing the Case**\n\nIn law, if you want to win against a precedent, you have to \"distinguish\" your case—meaning you have to prove your situation is different. Leo has two advantages that Googoo did not:\n\n1.  **The BCR:** Leo is operating under a formal Band Council Resolution (law). Googoo was operating more independently. Leo can argue he is following Indigenous Law, not just acting as an individual.\n2.  **The Lab Results:** Googoo's product had quality control issues. Leo's product is lab-certified clean. \n\n**Stare Decisis**\n\nHowever, the legal principle of **Stare Decisis** (standing by previous decisions) is strong. Judges hate to contradict other judges. If you can't find a strong enough reason to ignore the *Googoo* ruling, the system will pressure you to find Leo guilty.",
