        "primary": {
          "body": "## **THE MARSHALL LEGACY**\n\nThis entire case lives in the shadow of one man: **Donald Marshall Jr.**\n\nIn 1999, the Supreme Court of Canada ruled in *R. v. Marshall* that the 1760 Treaty gave Donald Marshall the right to catch and sell eels to earn a **\"Moderate Livelihood.\"** It was a landmark victory. It proved that the Treaties are real and enforceable rights to an economy.\n\n**The Definition Debate**\n\nHowever, the court defined \"Moderate Livelihood\" vaguely. It covers the \"necessaries\" of life—food, clothing, housing—but not the accumulation of vast wealth. It doesn't allow for a massive commercial enterprise.\n\n**Applying Marshall to Cannabis**\n\nIndigenous lawyers argue: \"The Treaty wasn't about eels. It was about *Trade*. It was about the economy. If we could trade fish then, we can trade cannabis now.\" \n\nIf you agree with Leo, you are expanding the *Marshall* decision to a new industry. You are saying that \"Moderate Livelihood\" includes the right to run a modern business. If you disagree, you are limiting *Marshall* to traditional items only, keeping the definition narrow. This decision will define what \"Livelihood\" means for the next generation.",
