        "legal": {
          "body": "## **THE SPARROW CHECKLIST**\n\nJudges don't just guess; they use a strict legal test called the **Sparrow Test** (from *R. v. Sparrow*, 1990) to decide if a government action is legal. As the clerk, you must walk through these four steps:\n\n**1. Is there an existing Right?**\nYes. The Treaty of 1752 clearly establishes a right to trade. This part is easy.\n\n**2. Did the Government infringe (break) that Right?**\nYes. The raid shut down Leo's shop. It stopped him from trading. The right was definitely infringed.\n\n**3. Was there a VALID OBJECTIVE?**\nThis is where it gets tricky. The Crown argues the objective is \"Public Safety.\" Usually, courts agree that safety is a valid reason to break a Treaty. (You can't claim a Treaty right to speed through a school zone).\n\n**4. Was the Honour of the Crown upheld?**\nThis is the final, critical hurdle. Even if the objective is valid, the government must act honourably. \n* Did they try to negotiate with Leo first?\n* Did they use **\"Minimal Impairment\"**? (Did they use the least forceful way to solve the problem?)\n\n**The Minimal Impairment Fail**\n\nThe Crown sent a SWAT team to raid a peaceful shop. Could they have just sent a health inspector? Could they have sent a letter? If the force was excessive, the infringement is illegal, *even if* the safety concern is real. Many legal experts believe the Crown fails on this step.",
